===Etymology===
{{PIE root|en|bʰeh₂|id=speak}}
From {{der|en|fr|aphasie}}, from {{der|en|grc|ἀφασία}}, from {{m|grc|ἄφατος||speechless}}, from {{m|grc|ἀ-||not}} + {{m|grc|φάσις||speech}}. Equivalent to {{confix|a|phasia|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/əˈfeɪzɪə/|/əˈfeɪʒə/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|pathology}} A [[partial]] or [[total]] [[loss]] of [[language]] [[skill]]s due to [[brain]] [[damage]]. Usually, damage to the left perisylvian region, including Broca's area and Wernicke's area, causes aphasia.
#* {{quote-journal|journal=Medical and Surgical Reporter|page=197|year=1865|volume=8|passage=The very disease '''aphasia''' is to most of us a new one; and we venture to say that even yet no one can give a satisfactory definition of Trousseau's new term.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7DegAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22aphasia%22&pg=PA197#v=onepage&q=%22aphasia%22&f=false|title=Discussions upon Aphasia}}
#* {{quote-journal|journal=Dublin quarterly journal of medical science|volume=39|title=On the Loss of Language in Cerebral Disease|author=J. T. Banks|passage=Of one form of '''aphasia''' we have an accurate description by Van Swieten, in his chapter on apoplexia:―"Vidi plures, qui ab apoplexiâ curati omnibus functionibus cerebri recte valebant, nisi quod deesset, hoc unicum, quod non possent vera rebus designandis vocabula invenire."|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fgQHAAAAcAAJ&dq=%22The%20venerable%20age%20of%20the%20term%20alalia%22&pg=PA63#v=onepage&q=aphasia&f=false|year=1865}}
#* '''1888''', {{w|Rudyard Kipling}}, "The Conversion of Aurelian McGoggin" in ''Plain Tales from the Hills'', Folio 2005, p. 76:
#*: The Doctor came over in three minutes, and heard the story. ‘It's '''''aphasia''''',’ he said.

